[src:react-native/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:react-native/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:react-native/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:react-native/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:react-native/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:react-native/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:react-native/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:react-native/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:react-native/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:react-native/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:react-native/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:react-native/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:react-native/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:react-native/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:react-native/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:react-native/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:react-native/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:react-native/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:react-native/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:react-native/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:react-native/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:react-native/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:react-native/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:react-native/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:react-native/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:react-native/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:react-native/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:react-native/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:react-native/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:react-native/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:react-native/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:react-native/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:react-native/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:react-native/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:react-native/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:react-native/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:react-native/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:react-native/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:react-native/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:react-native/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:react-native/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:react-native/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:react-native/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:react-native/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:react-native/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:react-native/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:react-native/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:react-native/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:react-native/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:react-native/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:react-native/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:react-native/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:react-native/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:react-native/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:react-native/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:react-native/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:react-native/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:react-native/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:react-native/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:react-native/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:react-native/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:react-native/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:react-native/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:react-native/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:react-native/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:react-native/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:react-native/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:react-native/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:react-native/native-computing] Native software is built to be executed directly by processors that implement a compatible instruction set.
[src:react-native/native-computing] A program that runs natively on one platform is runnable on another platform via an emulator if an emulator is available and, generally, with significant runtime speed degradation.
[src:react-native/native-computing] For example, games for a Game Boy (typically distributed as a cartridge), generally run natively on a Game Boy which is relatively incompatible with other computer platforms.
[src:react-native/native-computing] To run such a game on another processor, software that emulates the Game Boy hardware is required.
[src:react-native/native-computing] Cross-platform software can run on multiple processors although possibly requiring it to be re-built for different target systems.
[src:react-native/native-computing] A native application programming interface (API) provides direct access to an underlying technology.
[src:react-native/native-computing] For example, the Windows Native API is an application programming interface specific for the Windows NT kernel, which provides access to some kernel functions which cannot be directly accessed through the more universal Windows API.
[src:react-native/native-computing] A native virtual machine (VM) runs directly on hardware, without virtualization or virtualization at its lowest level.
[src:react-native/native-computing] For example, with multiple levels of virtualization, the lowest level operating system – the one that actually maintains direct control of the hardware – is referred to as a "Native VM".
[src:react-native/native-computing] Applied to data, native data formats or communication protocols are those supported by a certain computer hardware or software, with maximal consistency and minimal amount of additional components.
[src:react-native/native-computing] For example, EGA and VGA video adapters *natively* support code page 437.
[src:react-native/native-computing] This does not preclude supporting other code pages, but it requires either a font uploading or using graphic modes.
[src:react-native/react-native] In 2012 Mark Zuckerberg commented, "The biggest mistake we made as a company was betting too much on HTML5 as opposed to native".
[src:react-native/react-native] Using HTML5 for Facebook's mobile version resulted in an unstable application that retrieved data slowly.
[src:react-native/react-native] He promised Facebook would soon deliver a better mobile experience.
[src:react-native/react-native] Inside Facebook, Jordan Walke developed software that generated UI elements for iOS from a background JavaScript thread, which became the basis for the React web framework.
[src:react-native/react-native] They decided to organize an internal hackathon to perfect this prototype in order to be able to build native apps with this technology.
[src:react-native/react-native] In 2015, after months of development, Facebook released the first version for the React JavaScript Configuration.
[src:react-native/react-native] During a technical talk, Christopher Chedeau explained that Facebook was already using React Native in production for its Group App and its Ads Manager App.
[src:react-native/react-native] In October 2025, Meta announced that it would donate React, React Native, and JSX (JavaScript XML) to a new React Foundation, part of the Linux Foundation.
[src:react-native/react-native] The working principles of React Native are virtually identical to React except that React Native does not manipulate the DOM via the Virtual DOM.
[src:react-native/react-native] It runs in a background process (which interprets the JavaScript written by the developers) directly on the end-device and communicates with the native platform via serialized data over an asynchronous and batched bridge.
[src:react-native/react-native] React components wrap existing native code and interact with native APIs via React's declarative UI paradigm and JavaScript.
[src:react-native/react-native] TypeScript is often used over JavaScript in modern React Native applications due to its increased type safety.
[src:react-native/react-native] While React Native styling has a similar syntax to CSS, it does not use HTML or CSS.
[src:react-native/react-native] Instead, messages from the JavaScript thread are used to manipulate native views.
[src:react-native/react-native] Using plugins, Tailwind can also be used with React Native.
[src:react-native/react-native] React Native is also available for both Windows and macOS, which is currently maintained by Microsoft.
[src:react-native/react-software] React can be used to develop single-page, mobile, or server-rendered applications with frameworks like Next.js and React Router.
[src:react-native/react-software] Because React is only concerned with the user interface and rendering components to the DOM, React applications often rely on libraries for routing and other client-side functionality.
[src:react-native/react-software] A key advantage of React is that it only re-renders those parts of the page that have changed, avoiding unnecessary re-rendering of unchanged DOM elements.
[src:react-native/react-software] React is used by an estimated 6% of all websites.
[src:react-native/react-software] React adheres to the declarative programming paradigm.
[src:react-native/react-software] Developers design views for each state of an application, and React updates and renders components when data changes.
[src:react-native/react-software] This is in contrast with imperative programming.
[src:react-native/react-software] React code is made of entities called components.
[src:react-native/react-software] These components are modular and can be reused.
[src:react-native/react-software] React applications typically consist of many layers of components.
[src:react-native/react-software] The components are rendered to a root element in the DOM using the React DOM library.
[src:react-native/react-software] The two primary ways of declaring components in React are through function components and class components.
[src:react-native/react-software] Since React v16.8, using function components is the recommended way.
[src:react-native/react-software] Function components, announced at React Conf 2018, and available since React v16.8, are declared with a function that accepts a single "props" argument and returns JSX (JavaScript XML).
[src:react-native/react-software] Function components can use internal state with the `useState` Hook.
[src:react-native/react-software] On February 16, 2019, React 16.8 was released to the public, introducing React Hooks.
[src:react-native/react-software] Hooks are functions that let developers "hook into" React state and lifecycle features from function components.
[src:react-native/react-software] Notably, Hooks do not work inside classes — they let developers use more features of React without classes.
[src:react-native/react-software] React provides several built-in hooks such as `useState`, `useContext`, `useReducer`, `useMemo` and `useEffect`.
[src:react-native/react-software] Others are documented in the Hooks API Reference.
[src:react-native/react-software] `useState` and `useEffect`, which are the most commonly used, are for controlling state and side effects, respectively.
[src:react-native/react-software] "Only call hooks from React functions" — do not call hooks from plain JavaScript functions so that stateful logic stays with the component.
[src:react-native/react-software] Although these rules cannot be enforced at runtime, code analysis tools such as linters can be configured to detect many mistakes during development.
[src:react-native/react-software] The rules apply to both usage of Hooks and the implementation of custom Hooks, which may call other Hooks.
[src:react-native/react-software] Though a similar concept to Server Side Rendering, RSCs do not send corresponding JavaScript to the client as no hydration occurs.
[src:react-native/react-software] As a result, they have no access to hooks.
[src:react-native/react-software] Class components are declared using ES6 classes.
[src:react-native/react-software] They behave the same way that function components do, but instead of using Hooks to manage state and lifecycle events, they use the lifecycle methods on the `React.Component` base class.
[src:react-native/react-software] React itself does not come with built-in support for routing.
[src:react-native/react-software] React is primarily a library for building user interfaces, and it does not include a full-fledged routing solution out of the box.
[src:react-native/react-software] Third-party libraries can be used to handle routing in React applications, such as React Router.
[src:react-native/react-software] It allows the developer to define routes, manage navigation, and handle URL changes in a React-friendly way.
[src:react-native/react-software] Another notable feature is the use of a virtual Document Object Model, or Virtual DOM.
[src:react-native/react-software] React creates an in-memory data-structure, similar to the browser DOM.
[src:react-native/react-software] Every time components are rendered, the result is compared with the virtual DOM.
[src:react-native/react-software] It then updates the browser's displayed DOM efficiently with only the computed differences.
[src:react-native/react-software] This process is called **reconciliation**.
[src:react-native/react-software] This allows the programmer to write code as if the entire page is rendered on each change, while React only renders the components that actually change.
[src:react-native/react-software] This selective rendering provides a major performance boost.
[src:react-native/react-software] When `ReactDOM.render` is called again for the same component and target, React represents the new UI state in the Virtual DOM and determines which parts (if any) of the living DOM needs to change.
[src:react-native/react-software] Lifecycle methods for class-based components use a form of hooking that allows the execution of code at set points during a component's lifetime.
[src:react-native/react-software] JSX, or JavaScript XML, is an extension to the JavaScript language syntax.
[src:react-native/react-software] Similar in appearance to HTML, JSX provides a way to structure component rendering using syntax familiar to many developers.
[src:react-native/react-software] React components are typically written using JSX, although they do not have to be (components may also be written in pure JavaScript).
[src:react-native/react-software] During compilation, JSX is converted to JavaScript code.
[src:react-native/react-software] JSX is similar to another extension syntax created by Facebook for PHP called XHP.
[src:react-native/react-software] The basic architecture of React applies beyond rendering HTML in the browser.
[src:react-native/react-software] For example, Facebook has dynamic charts that render to `<canvas>` tags, and Netflix and PayPal use universal loading to render identical HTML on both the server and client.
[src:react-native/react-software] React can also be used to develop native apps for Android and iOS using React Native.
[src:react-native/react-software] Server-side rendering (SSR) refers to the process of rendering a client-side JavaScript application on the server, rather than in the browser.
[src:react-native/react-software] This can improve the performance of the application, especially for users on slower connections or devices.
[src:react-native/react-software] With SSR, the initial HTML that is sent to the client includes the fully rendered UI of the application.
[src:react-native/react-software] This allows the client's browser to display the UI immediately, rather than having to wait for the JavaScript to download and execute before rendering the UI.
[src:react-native/react-software] React supports SSR, which allows developers to render React components on the server and send the resulting HTML to the client.
[src:react-native/react-software] This can be useful for improving the performance of the application, as well as for search engine optimization purposes.
[src:react-native/react-software] React does not attempt to provide a complete application library.
[src:react-native/react-software] It is designed specifically for building user interfaces and therefore does not include many of the tools some developers might consider necessary to build an application.
[src:react-native/react-software] This allows the choice of whichever libraries the developer prefers to accomplish tasks such as performing network access or local data storage.
[src:react-native/react-software] Common patterns of usage have emerged as the library matures.
[src:react-native/react-software] To support React's concept of unidirectional data flow (which might be contrasted with AngularJS's bidirectional flow), the *Flux* architecture was developed as an alternative to the popular model–view–controller architecture.
[src:react-native/react-software] Flux features *actions* which are sent through a central *dispatcher* to a *store*, and changes to the store are propagated back to the view.
[src:react-native/react-software] When used with React, this propagation is accomplished through component properties.
[src:react-native/react-software] Since its conception, Flux has been superseded by libraries such as Redux and MobX.
[src:react-native/react-software] Flux can be considered a variant of the observer pattern.
[src:react-native/react-software] A React component under the Flux architecture should not directly modify any props passed to it, but should be passed callback functions that create *actions* which are sent by the dispatcher to modify the store.
[src:react-native/react-software] The action is an object whose responsibility is to describe what has taken place: for example, an action describing one user "following" another might contain a user id, a target user id, and the type `USER_FOLLOWED_ANOTHER_USER`.
[src:react-native/react-software] The stores, which can be thought of as models, can alter themselves in response to actions received from the dispatcher.
[src:react-native/react-software] This pattern is sometimes expressed as "properties flow down, actions flow up".
[src:react-native/react-software] Many implementations of Flux have been created since its inception, perhaps the most well-known being Redux, which features a single store, often called a single source of truth.
[src:react-native/react-software] In February 2019, `useReducer` was introduced as a React hook in the 16.8 release.
[src:react-native/react-software] It provides an API that is consistent with Redux, enabling developers to create Redux-like stores that are local to component states.
[src:react-native/react-software] React was created by Jordan Walke, a software engineer at Facebook, Inc.
[src:react-native/react-software] (now Meta), who initially developed a prototype called "F-Bolt" before later renaming it to "FaxJS".
[src:react-native/react-software] This early version is documented in Jordan Walke's GitHub repository.[1] Influences for the project included XHP, an HTML component library for PHP.
[src:react-native/react-software] React was first deployed on Facebook's News Feed in 2011 and subsequently integrated into Instagram in 2012.
[src:react-native/react-software] React Native, which enables native Android, iOS, and UWP development with React, was announced at Facebook's React Conf in February 2015 and open-sourced in March 2015.
[src:react-native/react-software] On April 18, 2017, Facebook announced React Fiber, a new set of internal algorithms for rendering, as opposed to React's old rendering algorithm, Stack.
[src:react-native/react-software] React Fiber was to become the foundation of any future improvements and feature development of the React library.
[src:react-native/react-software] The actual syntax for programming with React does not change; only the way that the syntax is executed has changed.
[src:react-native/react-software] React's old rendering system, Stack, was developed at a time when the focus of the system on dynamic change was not understood.
[src:react-native/react-software] Stack was slow to draw complex animation, for example, trying to accomplish all of it in one chunk.
[src:react-native/react-software] Fiber breaks down animation into segments that can be spread out over multiple frames.
[src:react-native/react-software] Likewise, the structure of a page can be broken into segments that may be maintained and updated separately.
[src:react-native/react-software] JavaScript functions and virtual DOM objects are called "fibers", and each can be operated and updated separately, allowing for smoother on-screen rendering.
[src:react-native/react-software] On September 26, 2017, React 16.0 was released to the public.
[src:react-native/react-software] React 16.0 introduced error boundaries, a new component type that catches JavaScript errors anywhere in its child tree and renders a fallback UI instead of crashing the app.
[src:react-native/react-software] On October 20, 2020, the React team released React v17.0, notable as the first major release without major changes to the React developer-facing API.
[src:react-native/react-software] On March 29, 2022, React 18 was released which introduced a new concurrent renderer, automatic batching and support for server side rendering with Suspense.
